The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It probably won't be long before he arrives.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunication Office (TB), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the latest steps by the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send it from home.
How is it possible for prices in the Czech Republic to remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Bureau (TBT), Pavel Dvosak, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a marked decline in prices to which the classic operators must have reacted as well.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market, similar voices were heard both here and there.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators lies in the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, they have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large expenses in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages which, however, is often countered by the offer of tighter services.
For example, Tesco mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial goal group.
This operator specifically targets man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – he’s the operator he likes and can be trusted,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works with this virtual operator.
It’s hard to say if such a concept as that of Poland could hook on our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav ?epick? said: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be some virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it’s about launching Mobilking in other countries in our region,” Jana Studniková, a spokesman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone conversation on mobile.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real Telefónica O2 competition in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in this, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings,” said the group’s spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they sparkle better times.
It seems that, due to unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sr?e?, spokesman for Telefonica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market is referred to by other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2’s opinion, adds: “Until today we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop.”
“On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that it was possible to study in such a short horizon.
Vodafone is focusing on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Sepick adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this is when it comes to spending and infrastructure sharing.
We see it as the biggest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is to partner with a partner to establish a shared network for fast internet on mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to achieve something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on the T was at the time of U:fon’s entry by the T-Mobile company.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the T’s web pages.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: “Furthermore, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that another player’s entry into the market would mean great requirements for him and, above all, for his services.”
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just about the position of the TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Bidding (OHS).
However, she expressed her typical stance on this issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on renting the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was closed.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for the classic operators," Kristián Chalupa, from the foreign affairs department of the OHS, added to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than a consideration, apart from that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the drop in prices of mobile phone services"
Of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and the fall in prices are not in the interest of OHS.
What is truly shocking about all of this is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
“The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecom regulators,” Chalupa added.
Interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of conflict.
There is, of course, a relevant market analysis prepared by the IOT according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech traders has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator – with all its logic – has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for OHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly alike.
The current complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they face many similar impediments.
Carrying the responsibility in the IT is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the OHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately recently a new amendment was introduced to the telecommunications law for the expansion of the competition of the TB in the field of commercial tenders that was not carried out, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of OHS must know this well, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
Everything is fine when no one is watching
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator that already exists in Czech mobile phone networks remains unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
Usually these are companies that are engaged in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the carrier, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the trade conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases such as those cited were discovered, we could talk about breaches of contract conditions that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová replied to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned that it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make not negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav ?epick? warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible both percent of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card of their phone is not in their name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the carriers.
This is exactly what should seem to you minimally strange.
There is also a new question for OHS.
If mobile carriers turn their eyes on this type of procedure, why do they block the virtual carrier’s entry?
It is necessary to add that the OHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activities and if you do not want to, you should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this outbreak.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases did they defend the operators but their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and more began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this case goes through as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the attributions in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market is likely to start moving again.
If one of the carriers lets in a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And perhaps we will stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
