This is what is extracted from the letter that is stored in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With this desire, some groups of Sudeten Germans were presumably addressed to the President of the United States in 1945.
It results from the letters that are kept in a particular archive and that today are kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
In a letter to the U.S. president, the Germans asked that he not allow the return of the "Umava Land" - occupied by Hitler under the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
“We have correctly understood the situation and we really want your word that American units are coming to German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators,” the letter reads, signed with a “people who carry the fate of Umava in their hearts.”
In view of the fact that the union of Czechoslovakia with the southeastern Germans presumably represents - according to their Czech national character - a hope only in brutality, disregard, incomprehension, pressure and slavery, the authors plead in the letter to the American president that he should assume, for today and forever, the Umava under a protectorate.
“We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million people, we surrender ourselves to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way contributes to the victory of the Allies,” the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is presumably the fear of retaliation from the “Czech oppressors.”
If the president of the United States presumably doubted this idea of the Germans, it would suffice to organize a referendum on the lands of the United States on whether its inhabitants want to be part of the United States or live under its patronage.
Although the text of the letter, with the current knowledge of post-war history, may sound a little childish, according to some specialists paints closely the expectations of the Germans of the southeast at the time.
Although the Czech Germans must have intuited minimally that it was going to be about their expulsion from the republic, only a few admitted this possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Britain would negotiate for the Sudetenland some clear form of autonomy.
Others thought they would stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed even by Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who was born in Cheské Budajovice.
He was in the war, as a German from Budajovice, enlisted in the Baltic navy.
When at the end of the war the British seized him and placed him in the prison camp of Holstein dozens of Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
“They thought that when they came home, the Czech would be good for them,” Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners who lived before the war in Czechoslovakia, according to him, expected that on the basis of Bene's decrees they would be removed from the Republic.
