I think animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far, although we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case at least we can expect it because all human brains have the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we devote ourselves to other species and include questions about sensation and consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as other animals: it becomes dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, of which some scientists make conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Of course I don't think so.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to infect our subjective experience with that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated by the human consciousness of the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (because of their participation in short memory and executive functions that direct behavior).
This broad part is much more developed in the case of people than that of other primates and seems to be absolutely missing in other creatures.
Considering at least the aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex, including knowledge about who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is a reason to assume that even man differs from other primates.
Another peculiarity lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since most of his experience is linked to the language, that often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals may be excluded.
But even though consciousness would not depend on language, it would influence it so that the consciousness of animals, created as it is, in many cases would differ from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is difficult to explain how the consciousness of other animals works.
If that, as something interesting and subjective, is not measured because it has the special hardware, nor is it analyzed through our experiences, then your research presents us with big problems.
Most of my interventions relate to the content of the conscious experience, but at the same time there is also another aspect of consciousness that would have to be easier for scientific research.
One could investigate the consciousness processes of animals without taking into account their contents, and that is what happens during the studies of short memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But with this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, the essential passes to the neutral correlates of consciousness rather than to causal mechanisms: The two may or may not be alike.
Interestingly, this approach highlights the importance of the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex for visualization formation.
And what happens to the sensations?
I owe it to the fact that in the emotional system a part of the brain is activated that is responsible for that, as is the case with fear.
What we describe as fear is therefore a state of mind in which we are when the activity of the brain occupies a space of the defense system (or its consequences such as body reactions).
Seen from this point of view the sensations are very attached to part of the cerebral cortex which distinguishes primates and especially man.
From the point of view of linguistic nature they follow classifications of fine sensations because we can differentiate and classify states with the help of words and grammar to be able to describe the states of others apart from ourselves.
