Eatonville, the first fully black-inhabited city incorporated into the country and home of Zora Neale Hurston’s childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: “the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 men of color, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools and not a prison.”
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described – making it also a tourist stage by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Depression Season Federal Writers Project – remains a stand-alone place.
The city remains as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Mrs. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true ideas with the white man, who “knows so little about us and doesn’t know what’s missing.”
Even now, in the year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has called attention to starting a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain cautious in front of the outsider.
“We are very cautious about the way our story is told,” said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and a member of the city’s oldest church.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historical model of black affirmation and a community of nearly 2,400 people living under a level of poverty twice the national average.
It is a literary center, but also a repaired example of the rural culture of the black South – sometimes disdained, sometimes praised – that was born out of slavery in America.
Not surprisingly, those who reside here are both proud and reserved.
And the preoccupation with the image of Eatonville really started with Zora, as no one here calls her Mrs. Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her profound dialect books such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through downtown Florida often forgotten in the history of blacks and human drama.
Having a concrete face in both life and literature, Mrs. Hurston took her readers to the store owned by the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then into more private areas.
“Out of the road to the left,” he wrote, “there is the modern public brown school with its white finishes, its well-maintained gardens and playgrounds, cared for by Howard Miller, as he can barely read and write.”
She also mentions widow Dash's new husband and writes that Glenn Lee "sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with transient rooms."
So, in just a few hundred words, Mrs Hurston links Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Obviously, this Fodor didn't do it.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
"Zora described it as it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls Mrs. Hurston immortalized by quoting men who were singing colorless songs about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like that."
Mrs. Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who returned frequently after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Franklin Augusto, 77, remembers that when Mrs. Hurston arrived in town, she did so without warning in a large Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today prides itself on dressing with dignity.
Most residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed sarcastically.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin continues.
But, he adds, swinging in his chair in a backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Mrs. Hurston was probably baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Mrs. Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no great commemorative ceremonies, no great public readings.
“I don’t think her contribution to the world or her legacy was understood,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a 2003 biography of Mrs. Hurston.
