Speak asleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up very spabulous telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while sleeping.
The first time it happens, you get scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somnillochios.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a monthS...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (fall asleep) or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitement situations.
However, it is a poorly studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a whisper or quite the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives you exit in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress chart).
What you can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will allow the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the sleeping pills appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
