Sarkozy Finds Angry Fishers
Before taking off to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will give a roundup for Brittany.
Faced with the demonstration of resistance by fishermen that strongly disturbed the entrances of several Breton and Norman ports last Monday, the president of the Republic decided to go last Tuesday morning to the port of Guilvinec, in the Finistère, to find their representatives there.
They promised to welcome him “in a constructive spirit” and hoped that he would “come with concrete proposals”.
This presidential visit coincides with the general meeting of the "committee of crisis" created by the Breton fishermen to achieve measures in the face of the increase in the prices of diesel, which marks a record when reaching 1.14 euros per liter.
According to Elysee spokesman David Martinon, the president “will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their companies to become competitive again and to save the conditions of jobs and remuneration of sailors.”
The fishermen are waiting for Nicolas Sarkozy on their feet.
On Tuesday morning, they carried out operations to reduce circulation in the Morbihan and Calvados, which have resulted in traffic jams of almost 10 km.
The marina of Quiberon has also been blocked, but connections to Belle-île have not been stopped.
“A filter barrier” has been placed on the Quiberon Peninsula.
Sailors on Monday showed their determination by burning tyres and wooden pallets in front of fuel tanks in the ports of Brest and Lorient, while demonstrations took place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, such as at Les Sables d'Olonne, in Vandea, where the oxen stayed in the port, or at Le Havre, where some twenty ships blocked the movements of commercial ships.
The fishermen of La Turballe and Croisic, in the Loire-Atlantic region, stopped in the afternoon the blockade of the important Total refinery of Donges.
The fishermen of Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait until this Wednesday’s meeting that will take place at the ministry to think about possible actions.
In Guilvinec, the “crisis committee” will have to think on Tuesday about the development of the movement and its participation in the scheduled meeting at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials of the national fishing committee, which did not sustain their movement.
"The strike will continue " because " the fishermen did not give up " and " they do not want to move to Paris ", announced for example Liliane Cariou, the chairman of the Lorient fishing committee.
Professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 cents per liter but consider that the financial equilibrium point of a boat can be reached only with a diesel with a price of less than 0.30 euros per liter.
