Analysis of the historic session of the Paris Stock Exchange
The New York Stock Exchange reported a historic drop on Monday after the House rejected Paulson’s plan to save the banks: the Dow Jones lost 6.98%, a never-before-seen loss of nearly 800 points, and the Nasdaq by 9.14%.
The Dow Jones Industrial Index fell from 777.68 to 10,365.45 points.
In terms of points, the largest drop in its history (684.81 points) had been recorded in the past on 17 September 2001, the day on which exchanges began again after the terrorist attacks of 11 September.
The technology-dominant Nasdaq index fell 199.61 points to 1,983.73 units and the expanded Standard & Poor’s 500 index by 8.81% (i.e. 106.85 points) to 1,106.55 units, according to the final closing figures.
Already depressed by the crisis at the beginning of the session, Wall Street sank after the House unexpected rejection of the plan to save the banks that would have allowed it to regain some stability in the markets.
With 228 votes against and 205 in favor, representatives denied U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson the media he called for.
Nearly two in three Republicans rejected his plan.
“That’s not a good signal sent to the market that Congress is unable to adopt a plan,” said Lindsey Piegza of the FTN Financial.
“This shows how far the market had this plan,” added Lindsey Piegza, fearing that a project adopted within several days would come “too late.”
“If the project is really dying... the Fed and other central banks will quickly take over to manage the crisis, which would tighten credit conditions more,” Brian Bethune, head of economics and finance at Global Insight, said in a statement.
And further accentuating the sense of urgency, “every day that passes is announced the fall of a financial institution” in the United States, stressed Ms. Piegza.
After the bankruptcy of Washington Mutual last Friday, authorities arranged for the purchase of Wachovia’s banking activities by rival Citigroup.
In Europe, the crisis dramatically accelerated, prompting emergency interventions for the benefit of banks in the UK, Benelux, Iceland and Germany, which shows that markets are facing “not just a crisis in the US but a global crisis,” the FTN Financial analyst added.
The bond market has risen drastically.
The yield on the 10-year treasury bond fell by 3.632 percent, compared with 3.827 percent on Friday afternoon, and the 30-year treasury bond fell by 4.161 percent, compared with 4.357 percent the day before.
