On television, President Lukashenko and members of the Central Electoral Commission congratulate themselves on their success.
The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the confidence of the public that had been seriously faltered by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood supplies administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, presided over by Judge Horacio Krever, to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was slow to present their relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Society of Blood to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After making a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained the trust of the public,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that “trust is extremely fragile.”
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, Décary says.
And we didn’t know if this disease could be spread through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we institute measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleid acid tests that allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until now were based.
Nucleid acid testing shortened the period between when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk that certain donors are unknowingly infected and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means we’ll have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
Thus, since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I think you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health without worry,” said the head of management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You have to be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary pursues before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
“The needs increase as the population ages.
Since anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network which brings together on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.”
All people in good health, 18 years old and who meet the admissibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain it and incite it to be a regular donor.
Since current life is very unbridled, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating her blood,” says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago, the placing on the bank of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
“Many mothers are disappointed that they can’t enjoy this,” because Héma-Québec doesn’t have the resources to propose this complex and costly program in every hospital in Quebec.
