Charest takes care of the North
The Prime Minister does not rule out launching elections before the end of the year
As soon as the general council of the Liberal Party ends, Jean Charest was yesterday in Juan-Talon, Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), tries to get elected during today’s by-election.
Rejecting the Boundaries of Our Last Great Northern Frontier: Such is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force by staying on the big lines, at the end of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis, yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, images were projected.
They were parading, on three huge screens, spectacular images of hydroelectric reservoirs, mining, Quebec seen by "Google Maps", maps, etc.
Big media like during the election period.
The prime minister thinks the election will take place this fall, although he made it clear that his schedule was very full.
The "Northern Plan" is the fourth side of a "vision" that the prime minister intends to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic space", which includes an agreement on labor with France, an alliance between Canada and Europe and harmonies with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the speeches of the prime minister recently, the opening of the North - the northern territory to the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
The prime minister, however, limited himself to explaining why the North was “a jewel to the immense potential,” but gave no term, investment amounts, or precise priority in future projects.
What could especially be more developed are: particularly hydroelectricity, the forest, but especially the mining sector, doped by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and also diamond," according to Mr. Charest's enumeration.
This "twice as big a territory as France," is our home, it's in Quebec.
Not only is it home to us, but it is in us,” he insisted, as if to show that he solicited a national founding myth.
Quebec was greatly built thanks to its relationship with the North, he stressed: the gold rush at Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
“It belongs to us, it’s our future,” he added, after taking a theatrical pause to contemplate the immense map behind it.
The North, 70 percent of Quebec’s territory, comprises a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the prime minister said at the press conference.
“It’s a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line in which they have not agreed for a long time and, when the occasion presents itself, I reiterate that position on the part of the government,” he said.
In addition, “with climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North,” he said, referring to the Northwest Passage, which will open each year due to melting ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister considers it a duty to occupy the territory.
And the inhabitants of the territory, the First Nations and the Inuit?
The prime minister said the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, particularly young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former deputy of Ungava’s Quebec party), have already begun consultations with about 30 communities.
An interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) plays an important role began some work.
The prime minister does not rule out an important meeting, “not necessarily a summit,” but a meeting in which “a common vision will be given.”
The development of the North would be in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan “will be concerted, orderly and environmentally friendly,” he promised.
Jean Charest described this “vision” as one that is in continuity with that of the liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
“Like the liberals who preceded us, we have thought otherwise to transform challenges into new opportunities for growth and development.”
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began on Friday with a large cocktail to mark the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage’s rise to power.
One of the adopted resolutions proposes to rename the Beauharnois Plant in Adélard-Godbout Reservoir.
“From Godbout, who created HydroQuebec, in Lesage who made the Quiet Revolution and the nationalization of hydroelectricity, in Bourassa who made James Bay our party knew how to forge the future,” said Juan Charest.
In the press conference, he invoked another reference, that conservative, the "Roads to the North" program of John Diefenbaker, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
Touching on the topic of the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Mr. Charest stressed that its commissioning is scheduled for 2012.
“This stays among us, but I plan to be there,” he confided to his militants, eliciting applause.
Indeed, the prime minister, who said in April that elections would not take place in 2008 and certainly not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of a vote this fall, which the law allows him.
He points out that his schedule is nonetheless full, particularly because of a federation council mission to China and a Quebec-New York City summit.
The weekend general council provided the liberal chief with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, particularly "constitutional aspirations" that had no problems to be accepted: the Liberal Party of Quebec in particular calls for recognition of the "specificity of Quebec" in the Constitution.
He also hoped that Quebec would appoint members of the Canadian Broadcasting and Telecommunications Council and that they would have a veto over the decisions taken in Quebec.
On the opposition side, we welcome the broad lines of the Northern Plan with skepticism.
The head of the Quebec party, Pauline Marois, highlighted the North Quebec Development Policy that the Landry government had launched in 2001.
According to her, the Liberal government, coming to power in 2003, renounced its application.
If she had done so, “we would have made progress today,” said Ms. Marois alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (vote that took place today), Françoise Mercure.
The Quebec Democratic Action seemed to support the government’s adoption of a Northern Plan.
“But what is desired is that this is not just a show,” said leader Sebastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who returns on vacation today.
