Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining firm Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world’s largest gold company attempted a defamation lawsuit of six million euros against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation persecution, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to their own?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the miner.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly arrangement that will gag the opposition as well as scare anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by knocking.
It was enough for the miner to open her books, her files and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a “public” debate disregarding his views?
According to the vice president, this word seems to designate only highly paid lawyers and not for all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, critics also have the right to speak.
What he doesn’t understand – or what he doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so mainly because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
