Psychology of Overlays: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have discovered the neurological-economic underpinnings of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction, and in the meantime the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment were examined by the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI).
In both games participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called the stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-reward” mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in betting is explained as a prevention not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against a person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group even lost that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph stood out and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the neurologists’ hypothesis, the members of the group who played “against failure” were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the “win” group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For until now they explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
An estimated one hundred thousand people are infected in this country, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the patients do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread through two main forms: foodborne hepatitis A and E (for example with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
Travelers are advised to protect themselves with vaccines against the A and B viruses, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating the infected food, manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last as long as two to three weeks.
Every year one million people die in the world from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this disease agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical check-up, is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease is cured if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so that it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less who believes in God?
According to recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain.
In this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University participate alongside the academics.
The analysis took place as follows; they fixed a flashing instrument to the patient’s left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of Sassoferrato of the 17th century and the Lady of the Arminian Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary spectacle would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt “safe” as “protected” people, “they were reassured and peace reigned in their hearts.”
When they looked at the religious-themed picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
“We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like for a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
“Exercising faith should and in many cases really changes our personality,” Wright said.
After these formidable results only one question remains: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
