The smart car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the obstacles sensors existing in nature?
For example, the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C car robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, chief technology officer of PR and development and research.
Composite bumblebee eyes play an important role that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of composite eyes, the engineers used the laser-ray length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at a 180-degree angle, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle mimicking the movements of the bumblebees, modifying the direction by turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If not, the vehicle’s robot could not react quickly enough to dodge obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Lab and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in a snap.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotary movement and acceleration in addition to braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the capacity for data processing, let alone storage.
This apparatus in every second should only process a few input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
You don’t need gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge obstacles, which Nissan estimates will be able to incorporate into mass-produced models in ten years’ time.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination, dodging existing obstacles in their path.
