The written version of the $700 billion bailout law has been prepared, which will be implemented in several phases in order to buy bad loans from banks.
In the first phase, half the money will be spent.
According to East Coast timetables during new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion financial bailout package in total, after several days of discussion.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the U.S. Congress, saying the agreement was only to be formalized in a document.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise said: this program will work and be efficient but other measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the car of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. the Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 a.m. on Monday, according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock markets.
On the bill called the 2008 economic stabilization emergency law, the first U.S. Congress will vote on Monday and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also welcomed the news about the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program is different from the original Bush administration proposal to spend all of the $700 billion to buy bad-quality credit-fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, likely on Monday, from this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy securities worth of bad credit, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
This program will be controlled by a special body, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion can be spent after a new congressional decision.
According to the law the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it will be able to simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and securities of credit fund, in addition to other credits of the "poisonous" type as well.
The purchase can be made at auctions or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the troubling elements, for which companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said that the law ensures the necessary financial means, which can reach up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it be the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some major financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it,” he added.
Instead, the heads of banks that are in trouble and await state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensations, which the American slang simply calls parachutes of gold.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of aid from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys as part of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on gold parachutes, unless the bank’s failed boss retires.
By buying bad credits directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that bosses’ compensations are not overstated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations refer only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the program as well.
This is the first case in American history that will be in effect a legal limitation for the revenues of the CEOs - said the measure Democrat Barney Frank, president of the committee of Congress, responsible for financial services.
The state will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they will ultimately even be able to make profits with the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
Under the bill, over the next five years, the president will have to submit a proposal to Congress on how to return the financial sector’s losses to taxpayers.
Of course there were those on both sides who expressed reservations about the project.
This is not what American citizens have entrusted us, that is, they are not protecting taxpayer dollars," California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa said.
His fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur, said: The measures were urged by the same ones who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008 domestic industrial selling prices rose by 0.1 percent compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007’s prices – reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and fell 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose 0.7 percent from the previous month and 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose only to a minimum of 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose minimally, up 0.1 percent from July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to the 4.6 percent increase in bags and belts per month and the 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector (1.4 percent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a small extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the other sectors of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in August, firstly as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period – in domestic sales of the sectors of the processing industry – the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, there was a 13.2 percent increase, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industries, there was an 11 percent increase.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electric machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the global processing industry, prices rose by 10.2 percent.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water exceeded the previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3 percent, with prices in the energy sector and the intermediate sectors unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediary industry (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods industries, there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods of 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a 3.9 percent decrease.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
