Járóka: The vicious cycle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities was launched in Paris, its host being France, which this year is also the President of the European Union.
Livia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message addressed to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that plague Roma children and it is also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was inaugurated - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for Jobs, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights organisations.
Járóka - according to the press office of the group of Fidesz deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, gypsies are left out of the labor market in the first place because of their low level of education.
“Most young Roma have not finished high school and because of the poor quality of basic education, only an insignificant part can earn a university degree.”
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, plays a decisive role in the predominance of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of EU member states.
According to the MEP, these issues need to be made widely known both among Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the earlier a gypsy student starts school, the more chances he will have to become an active member of the labor market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
“Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education,” said Livia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up immediately the processes of school desegregation, for which it is of fundamental importance to correctly comply with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
“We must break the vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility of guaranteeing democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens,” he said.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, held annually since last year’s Berlin meeting in the name of the “European Year of Equal Opportunities”, is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
