MP3 Players Charged With Hearing Risk
Listening to loud music over a long period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission says, which in a statement released in Bruxel cites the opinion of the Scientific Commission on the emerging and recently identified health risk (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
“From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day having the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability.”
“I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-acoustic cell phones can unconsciously ruin their ears in an irreparable way,” Kuneva said.
“From the scientific evidence a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What counts is raising awareness among consumers and making this information public.
We must also re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are broadly effective and have the pace with the new technology."
Bruxel had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the large use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that that causes.
“Scientists confirm that this is a cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what steps could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music and related devices.”
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but concern is increasing as the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these damages very much by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and the time of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices listen to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours a week exceed the limit currently in force relative to the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing after a period of 5 years.
